  "alternatingKneeHugsName": "Alternating Knee Hugs",
  "alternatingKneeHugsText": "Meaning:\r\nYou mobilize your hip flexors and strengthen your abdominal muscles at the same time. Additionally, you release tension in the lower back and get fit for your daily life. Prevention: By regularly mobilizing your hips and lower back, you can prevent stiff hip flexors and tense muscles in the lower back – two possible causes of back pain.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1. Lie down on your back and pull one knee toward your chest as if sending a friendly greeting to your leg.\r\n2. Keep the other leg straight and then switch sides. You can perform the movement a little faster to simultaneously strengthen your abdominal muscles.\r\n",
  "bwsRotationName": "4-Footed Thoracic Spine Rotation",
  "bwsRotationText": "Meaning:\r\nYour thoracic spine (T-spine) is often a forgotten hero when it comes to mobility. When we sit a lot, the T-spine becomes stiff and immobile, leading to tension in the upper back and neck. This rotation helps improve mobility in this area.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1. Start in a tabletop position, with knees under the hips and hands directly under the shoulders.\r\n2. Place one hand behind your head and gently rotate, bringing the elbow toward the opposite hand and then opening up.\r\n3. Imagine you're opening an old, stuck cabinet – slowly and deliberately. Let your gaze follow the hand.\r\n",
  "aufwachenderHundName": "Awakening Dog",
  "aufwachenderHundText": "Meaning: \r\nThis exercise is an easier variation of the Downward Dog. The movement lengthens the spine, opens the chest, and activates the back muscles – a true relief after long periods of sitting.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStart in a tabletop position, with knees under hips and hands directly under shoulders.\r\n2.\tPush yourself up through your hands, lift your hips toward the sky, and move your chest toward your knees.\r\n3.\tReturn to the tabletop position and begin again.",
  "babyRollingName": "Baby Rolling",
  "babyRollingText": "Meaning: \r\nDo you remember rolling carefree as a baby? This exercise is more than just fun: it improves the connection between the upper and lower body and promotes segmental movement of the spine. It enhances mobility and coordination throughout the body. This exercise provides functional mobility that many adults lack.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tLie on your back, stretch your arms and legs out as if you were ready for a nap.\r\n2.\tUse only one arm to slowly roll onto your stomach without moving your legs. Then do the same in reverse – just with your legs, while keeping your arms still.\r\n3.\tMake sure the movement is gentle and controlled – just like a baby would do!",
  "boxerCrunchName": "Boxer Crunch",
  "boxerCrunchText": "Meaning: \r\nImagine you're in a boxing ring, but instead of an opponent, you're fighting belly fat and instability! This exercise combines the power of a crunch with a dynamic rotational movement that primarily targets your oblique muscles.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tPosition your legs. Perform a crunch while making a punching motion with the opposite hand as if delivering the final blow to an invisible opponent!\r\n2.\tSwitch sides with each crunch and keep the movement controlled. Ensure your abdominal muscles, not momentum, are doing the work.",
  "kindToCobraName": "Child to Cobra",
  "kindToCobraText": "Meaning: \r\nThis sequence of the child and cobra pose gives you the best of both worlds: deep relaxation and active stretching. While the child pose gently stretches the lower back and hips, the cobra opens the chest, and alternately, you gently mobilize your spine.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStart in the child pose: knees on the ground, hips on the heels, arms stretched forward.\r\n2.\tGlide into the cobra pose by pushing your upper body forward and then opening your chest upwards. Your hips stay on the ground while you stretch your back.\r\n3.\tAlternate between the two positions, feeling the tension release while simultaneously mobilizing your spine. Breathe deeply in and out, as if you are moving gently like a wave.",
  "childPoseName": "Child Pose",
  "childPoseText": "Meaning: \r\nThe child pose is the ultimate relaxation pose. It gently stretches your back and opens the hips. Perfect for unwinding after a long day (or a tough workout).\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tKneel on the ground, big toes touching, knees slightly apart.\r\n2.\tSit back onto your heels and stretch your arms forward as you let your torso gently sink towards the ground.\r\n3.\tYour forehead touches the floor (or a blanket for extra comfort), and you breathe deeply in and out. Relax your entire back – as if you’re wrapping yourself in a cozy cocoon.",
  "dynamicSingleArmChildPoseName": "Dynamic Single-Arm Child Pose",
  "dynamicSingleArmChildPoseText": "Meaning: \r\nThis is a more mobile version of the classic child pose. By stretching one arm at a time, the entire chest and back muscles on the respective side are stretched. This can reduce tension in the neck and shoulders while improving upper body mobility – ideal for preventing shoulder pain.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStart in a quadruped position, leaving one arm on the ground while the other is bent. Push your hips back and feel the stretch.\r\n2.\tThen dynamically switch sides: moving gently from one arm to the other, allowing a smooth rocking motion.",
  "grosserGartenzwergName": "Great Garden Gnome",
  "grosserGartenzwergText": "Meaning: \r\nThis mobilization exercise for the hips and ankle joints comes from childhood development. Good hip mobility is the key to a stable and pain-free back.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStart in a prone position. Rise onto one side and place your foot in front of your knee.\r\n2.\tFeel the stretch in the back hip and keep your back long. Hold this pose for a moment, then switch to the other side.",
  "hipSwifelName": "Hip Swivel",
  "hipSwifelText": "Meaning: \r\nThis exercise mobilizes the hip joint and promotes rotational movement – a true all-rounder for hip mobility. Imagine lubricating your hip joint with a generous dose of motion oil. When the hips can rotate freely, pressure is relieved from the lumbar spine, preventing back and hip pain.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tSit on the floor, legs bent and spread wide apart. \r\n2.\tNow let both knees fall to one side. Your knees and shins lie flat on the floor. Let your hips sink further towards the ground.\r\n3.\tThen open at the knee and slowly rotate to the other side. Keep your upper body upright and feel the gentle rotation in your hips.",
  "hipSwifelLehnenName": "Hip Swivel Lean",
  "hipSwifelLehnenText": "Meaning: \r\nThis takes hip mobilization one step further – this time leaning forward to gain even more range of motion. This variation of the hip swivel exercise intensifies the stretch and creates additional space in the hip joint. Increased mobility in the hips ensures that movements otherwise compensated for in the lower back now occur directly in the hips.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tSit as you would for the regular hip swivel on the floor, legs bent and spread wide apart.\r\n2.\tYour knees now fall to one side. Knees and shins lie on the floor. Now lean forward with a long back. Try to bring your chest toward your foot.\r\n3.\tThen switch to the other side and start again.",
  "katzeKuhName": "Cat Cow",
  "katzeKuhText": "Meaning: \r\nThis classic movement from yoga promotes mobility throughout the spine – from the cervical to the lumbar vertebrae. Through the interplay of flexion and extension, you mobilize the back and support the supply of nutrients to your intervertebral discs.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStart in a tabletop position: knees under hips, hands under shoulders.\r\n2.\tInhale and arch your back like a happy cat – head and tailbone pointing upwards.\r\n3.\tExhale and round your back, curling up like a stretching cat. Your head sinks towards your chest, and your tailbone tucks in.\r\n4.\tAlternate between these two positions with your breath rhythm and feel your spine gradually relax and become more supple.",
  "kleineCobraLiftsName": "Small Cobra Lifts",
  "kleineCobraLiftsText": "Meaning: \r\nSmall cobra lifts are perfect as an entry-level exercise for the cobra pose. You open your entire body side from the toes to the forehead. If you experience pain, mark this exercise. Some individuals react negatively to spinal extensions. Provide feedback to your coach to adjust your training.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tLie on your stomach and place your elbows under your shoulders.\r\n2.\tPress your elbows into the floor. Gently lift your upper body just slightly off the ground and look up at the ceiling – imagine you are a small cobra cautiously emerging from its hiding spot.\r\n3.\tBreathe deeply toward your navel and relax the front of your body. Then lower yourself back down and start again.",
  "kneeHugName": "Knee Hug",
  "kneeHugText": "Meaning: \r\nThis exercise not only looks like a hug, but it also feels like one – for your hips and lower back. It improves the mobility of your hips and simultaneously stretches the muscles in your lower back to relieve tension.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tLie on your back, stretch your legs out, and then pull one knee to your chest as if lovingly hugging it.\r\n2.\tHold the position for a few seconds. Make sure your lower back stays flat on the floor. Breathe deeply and relax into the position. Then slowly switch sides.",
  "krabbelnMitTapName": "Crawling with Tap",
  "krabbelnMitTapText": "Meaning: \r\nHere comes movement! Crawling with Tap is a full-body exercise that not only promotes core stability but also improves coordination. Imagine you are an alert bear crawling through the woods, dynamically bringing your hand to the opposite knee for extra stability. This exercise strengthens the core muscles that ensure spinal stability, helping to prevent lower back overload.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tGet into the crawling position (tabletop), lift your knees slightly off the ground so only your hands and toes touch the floor.\r\n2.\tCrawl forward slowly, lightly tapping one hand to the opposite knee – alternating from left to right.\r\n3.\tKeep your back stable and your core tight. The tap is gentle but effective in training your core and improving mobility.",
  "langsitzFusskreiseName": "Seated Foot Circles",
  "langsitzFusskreiseText": "Meaning: \r\nThis is an exercise for the details – mobilizing your ankle joints. Flexible ankles are crucial for maintaining healthy biomechanics in the lower extremities. They help reduce pressure on the knees and hips by allowing for natural movement dynamics while walking and running.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tSit upright with your legs extended in front of you.\r\n2.\tSlowly and controlled, circle both feet clockwise and then counterclockwise.",
  "laufenderHundName": "Walking Dog",
  "laufenderHundText": "Meaning: \r\nA variation of the \"Downward Dog\" from yoga, in which you alternately bend and straighten your legs. This exercise aims to improve the flexibility of the backs of your legs. At the same time, the active stretching of the upper body enhances shoulder mobility, helping to prevent tension in the neck and shoulder area.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStart in the \"Downward Dog\" pose: hands firmly on the floor, hips pushed toward the sky, chest toward the knees.\r\n2.\tNow begin to alternately bend one leg while straightening the other – like a dog walking in place.\r\n3.\tSwitch sides in a fluid rhythm and feel the stretch in your legs and shoulders. Stay loose and enjoy the dynamic flow.",
  "rlNackenrotationenName": "Supine Neck Rotations",
  "rlNackenrotationenText": "Meaning: \r\nA simple yet highly effective exercise for neck mobilization, performed while lying on your back. Slowly turn your head from one side to the other, bringing movement back to the often stiff neck muscles. The gentle rotation can restore neck mobility, especially after prolonged smartphone use.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tLie comfortably on your back with your arms relaxed at your sides.\r\n2.\tSlowly turn your head to one side as if curiously looking around, and then to the other side.\r\n3.\tMove your head calmly and controlled, without jerking. Your neck should gradually relax – perfect for winding down at the end of the day.",
  "rolleZuSeitsitzName": "Roll to Side Sit",
  "rolleZuSeitsitzText": "Meaning: \r\nThis exercise combines dynamism and mobility by rolling from a supine position to a side sit. It mobilizes your hip muscles and uses the floor as a fascia roller for your back.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tLie relaxed on your back, arms stretched out to the sides.\r\n2.\tRoll up onto one side into a side sit, your knee placed in front of your foot.\r\n3.\tHold the position briefly and then roll back to the supine position. Switch sides and enjoy the smooth flow of movement.",
  "scapulaPushupName": "Scapula PushUp",
  "scapulaPushupText": "Meaning: \r\nThis push-up is a special variation that specifically targets the mobility and stability of the shoulder blades (scapulae). It trains the protraction and retraction of the shoulder blades, promoting long-term shoulder health. By specifically activating the muscles around the shoulder blades, this exercise stabilizes your shoulders and prevents overload and poor posture.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStart in a tabletop position: hands under shoulders, knees under hips.\r\n2.\tInstead of bending your arms, let your shoulder blades come together and then drift apart – imagine your shoulders are wings that first fold together and then spread out.\r\n3.\tKeep your arms straight throughout.",
  "ruckendehnungSchneidersitzName": "Cross-Legged Back Stretch",
  "ruckendehnungSchneidersitzText": "Meaning: \r\nIn this cross-legged pose, you stretch your arm to the side to stretch your latissimus, the large back muscle. At the same time, you open up your entire body side and help prevent back pain.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tSit cross-legged on the floor, then stretch one arm toward the ceiling.\r\n2.\tFeel the stretch in your back and continue breathing calmly. Then switch sides.",
  "triangleStretchName": "Triangle Stretch",
  "triangleStretchText": "Meaning: \r\nThe Triangle Stretch is a classic yoga pose that combines a side stretch of the upper body with the activation of the leg muscles. This exercise improves the flexibility of your sides while also enhancing stability.\r\n\r\nHow this exercise prevents pain: \r\nThe triangle stretch promotes the mobility of the lateral torso muscles and the hips. Regularly stretching your sides can help prevent back pain, often caused by tightness in the lateral muscles.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStand with your legs wide apart, arms stretched to the sides, as if forming a big \"T.\"\r\n2.\tBend to one side, letting your hand glide along your leg while stretching the other arm toward the sky.\r\n3.\tKeep your body in a straight line and feel the intense stretch on your side. Repeat on the other side – imagine becoming long and light, like a moving triangle.",
  "kaferAngewinkeltName": "Bent-Leg Bug",
  "kaferAngewinkeltText": "Meaning: \r\nThe bent-leg bug exercise strengthens your deep abdominal muscles and promotes spinal stability while alternating arm and leg movements. Imagine you’re a bug on your back, trying to coordinate its movements. By specifically activating the core muscles, this exercise helps prevent back pain, especially during activities that require a stable core.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tLie on your back, lift your legs, and bend them at a 90-degree angle. Stretch your arms upward.\r\n2.\tSlowly lower one arm and the opposite bent leg until they hover just above the floor, then return them to the starting position.\r\n3.\tSwitch sides and keep your core tightly engaged. Your lower back remains flat on the floor – the bug must not tip over!",
  "tuckedKrokodilatmungName": "Tucked Crocodile Breathing",
  "tuckedKrokodilatmungText": "Meaning: \r\nThis breathing exercise promotes diaphragmatic breathing and helps you build natural stability in your core with each breath. By expanding your diaphragm throughout your abdominal cavity, your breath generates intra-abdominal pressure, providing stability to your spine and enabling you to lift heavy objects more effectively.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStart lying on your back with your legs in a 90° angle in the air. Place your hands like clamps directly below your ribcage.\r\n2.\tBreathe deeply through your nose into your abdomen, so your hands move apart, and your fingers are pushed forward and backward. Feel the full 360° expansion of your diaphragm.",
  "seitlageOberschenkeldehnungName": "Side-Lying Quadriceps Stretch",
  "seitlageOberschenkeldehnungText": "Meaning: \r\nIn this position, you stretch the front of your thigh (quadriceps). This is a perfect exercise to open up the hips and improve flexibility in the thigh muscles. Regular stretching of these muscles helps prevent back and knee pain.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tLie on your side, resting your head on your arm to stay relaxed.\r\n2.\tUse your upper hand to grab your ankle and gently pull your foot toward your buttocks until you feel a comfortable stretch on the front of your thigh.\r\n3.\tEnsure your pelvis stays neutral, and you don’t arch your lower back. Hold this position and breathe calmly, as if lovingly stretching your muscles.",
  "supineRotationsName": "Supine Rotations",
  "supineRotationsText": "Meaning: \r\nThis exercise introduces a wonderful rotation to your spine and mobilizes the entire core and lumbar region. The movement is gentle yet profound – perfect for loosening the lower back and hips. Regular spinal rotations help relieve tension in the lower back and improve mobility.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tLie on your back with your arms stretched out to the sides like a \"T.\"\r\n2.\tBend your knees and let them slowly and gently fall to one side while keeping your upper body on the floor.\r\n3.\tReturn to the center and repeat the movement on the other side. Take deep breaths as you perform the rotation and feel your back gently release – like a cozy stretch after waking up.",
  "liegendeMeditationName": "Supine Meditation",
  "liegendeMeditationText": "Meaning: \r\nStress and tension are often the causes of physical pain, especially in the back and neck. Through conscious relaxation and breath control, this meditation can help relieve muscle tension, find mental calmness, and prevent pain.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tLie flat on your back, arms relaxed at your sides, with your palms facing up.\r\n2.\tClose your eyes and focus on your breathing. Let your breath flow deeply into your belly through your nose in a relaxed manner.\r\n3.\tAllow every part of your body to sink into the floor – like a feather gently coming to rest.",
  "barenhockeName": "Bear Squat",
  "barenhockeText": "Meaning: \r\nThis dynamic exercise mobilizes the hips and feet, strengthens the leg muscles, and improves core stability. Well-mobilized hips and stable leg muscles are essential to preventing knee and back discomfort.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStart in a kneeling position with your toes tucked and hands on the floor.\r\n2.\tThen lift your knees and push your heels toward the ground to feel a stretch across the entire underside of your feet.",
  "krabbePiriformisBeidseitigName": "Crab Piriformis Bilateral",
  "krabbePiriformisBeidseitigText": "Meaning: \r\nThis exercise stretches the piriformis muscle, which is deep in the hip and often responsible for pain in the lower back and hip. A relaxed and well-stretched piriformis prevents pressure on the sciatic nerve and helps avoid pain.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tSit on the floor, supporting yourself with your hands behind you, with your legs bent in front of you.\r\n2.\tLift your hips slightly off the floor, place one foot on the opposite knee, and let your hip sink to the side to stretch the piriformis.\r\n3.\tHold the position, take a deep breath, and then switch sides. Your body will feel relaxed and more flexible, as if it just had a timeout!",
  "krabbeScapulaPushUpName": "Crab Scapula Push-Up",
  "krabbeScapulaPushUpText": "Meaning: \r\nThis variation of the scapula push-up is performed in the crab position. Shoulder stability is essential to prevent neck and shoulder pain. By strengthening the muscles around the shoulder blades, you ensure that your shoulders remain stable during everyday movements and avoid overuse.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tSit in the crab position: hands on the floor behind you, feet flat, and lift your hips slightly.\r\n2.\tKeep your arms straight and push your shoulders away from your ears. Then let yourself sink until your shoulders are almost touching your ears.\r\n3.\tFeel when your shoulders are truly away from your ears and remember this position for everyday posture.",
  "gluteBridgeName": "Glute Bridge",
  "gluteBridgeText": "Meaning: \r\nThe glute bridge is an excellent exercise to activate and strengthen the gluteal muscles and hamstrings. It strengthens the entire posterior chain – from the lumbar spine to the glutes and legs.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tLie on your back, knees bent, feet hip-width apart.\r\n2.\tPush your heels into the floor and lift your hips until your body forms a straight line from your knees to your shoulders.\r\n3.\tHold the position for a few seconds, then lower your hips again. Squeeze your glutes firmly at the top – imagine crushing a walnut!",
  "knienderSeitplankTapsName": "Kneeling Side Plank Taps",
  "knienderSeitplankTapsText": "Meaning: \r\nThis exercise targets your lateral core muscles and stabilizes the shoulders. Strong lateral core muscles protect the spine from unwanted movements and help improve stability.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tGet into a kneeling side plank position, support yourself on your forearm, and lift the free arm upward.\r\n2.\tLift your hips until your body forms a straight line. Then bring the elbow and knee of the upper arm and leg together and stretch again.",
  "standSchulterkreiseName": "Standing Shoulder Circles",
  "standSchulterkreiseText": "Meaning: \r\nStiff shoulders? Not anymore with this exercise! Shoulder circles help relieve tension and stiffness caused by long periods of sitting. They promote blood circulation and improve shoulder health, helping to prevent shoulder pain.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStand upright with your arms relaxed at your sides.\r\n2.\tPerform gentle, circular movements with your shoulders forward and then backward, as if slowly turning a wheel.\r\n3.\tFeel the mobilization in your shoulder area and ensure your neck stays relaxed. This exercise feels like a little massage for your shoulders!",
  "gegratschteVorbeugeSideToSideName": "Wide-Legged Forward Bend Side to Side",
  "gegratschteVorbeugeSideToSideText": "Meaning: This exercise targets the flexibility of the hips and thighs by shifting from side to side in a wide-legged forward bend. By mobilizing the hips and stretching the hamstrings, you can reduce tension in the lower back.\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStand with your legs wide apart and bend forward with a straight back, placing your hands on the ground.\r\n2.\tWalk your hands over to one foot and feel the stretch in your back as well.\r\n3.\tThen slowly move to the other side.",
  "gegratschteVorbeugeMitRotationName": "Wide-Legged Forward Bend with Rotation",
  "gegratschteVorbeugeMitRotationText": "Meaning: \r\nThis variation of the forward bend adds a rotation of the upper body. By rotating the spine, you release tension in the back and improve thoracic spine mobility. This helps prevent back pain, often caused by a stiff spine.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStand in a wide-legged forward bend as described, with a straight back.\r\n2.\tExtend one hand upward while the other touches the ground or rests on your leg. Gently rotate your upper body to the side.\r\n3.\tHold the rotation, feel the stretch along your lateral core, and then switch sides. You’ll feel like gently wringing out your back – like a freshly washed towel!",
  "mountainPoseZuJeffersonCurlName": "Mountain Pose to Jefferson Curl",
  "mountainPoseZuJeffersonCurlText": "How does this exercise prevent pain: \r\nThis movement improves the mobility of the spine and hamstrings. The Jefferson Curl stretches and strengthens the lower back, helping to prevent back pain caused by stiffness in the spine and hamstrings.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStart in the Mountain Pose: feet hip-width apart, arms by your sides, standing tall and upright – like a mountain firmly rooted in the earth.\r\n2.\tRoll forward vertebra by vertebra into the Jefferson Curl, letting your head hang last, and feel the stretch along your entire spine and hamstrings.\r\n3.\tSlowly roll back up, performing the movement in a controlled manner as if moving each vertebra individually. Your back will feel loose and relaxed, like a flexible branch swaying in the wind.",
  "gegratschteVorbeugeRunterrollenName": "Wide-Legged Forward Bend Roll Down",
  "gegratschteVorbeugeRunterrollenText": "How does this exercise prevent pain: \r\nThis exercise combines a slow, controlled roll-down with a forward bend from a wide-legged position. The slow roll-down and stretching of the hamstrings release tension in the lower back and simultaneously improve hip mobility.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStand with your legs wide apart, approximately double shoulder-width.\r\n2.\tBegin rolling down slowly, vertebra by vertebra, starting with your head. Let your upper body hang heavy as you glide into the forward bend.\r\n3.\tPause briefly at the bottom, let your head relax, and feel the stretch in your hamstrings. Then roll back up in a controlled manner, as if gently unwinding and rewinding your spine.",
  "easyHockeZuVorbeugeName": "Easy Squat to Forward Bend",
  "easyHockeZuVorbeugeText": "How does this exercise prevent pain: \r\nBy alternating between a squat and a forward bend, you mobilize the hips and stretch the leg muscles, relieving tension in the lower back. The transitions are smooth and mobilize the entire posterior chain. This exercise prepares you perfectly for more advanced deep squat variations.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStart standing with your feet shoulder-width apart and heels on the ground.\r\n2.\tSlightly bend your knees and move into a gentle squat. Keep your gaze forward.\r\n3.\tNow straighten your legs and let your head hang slightly towards the floor. Feel the mobilization in your hips and repeat the sequence several times. Ensure the movement is controlled and follows your breathing rhythm.",
  "hockeReinkommenName": "Deep Squat Entry",
  "hockeReinkommenText": "How does this exercise prevent pain: \r\nA deep, stable squat is key to healthy hips and knees. By improving mobility in these areas, you can prevent pain caused by stiffness or overloading in the joints. It's a true all-rounder and improves the mobility of the hip joints, legs, and ankles.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStand shoulder-width apart, with your feet slightly turned out.\r\n2.\tSlowly lower into a deep squat by pushing your hips back and bending your knees, keeping your torso upright.\r\n3.\tGently shift from one side to the other. Your heels may lift alternately to simplify the exercise.",
  "hockeRotationZuVorbeugeName": "Squat Rotation to Forward Bend",
  "hockeRotationZuVorbeugeText": "How does this exercise prevent pain: \r\nRotating the spine helps to relieve tension in the entire back. The transition to a forward bend mobilizes the entire posterior chain and enhances your body's flexibility.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStart in a deep squat, with your feet slightly wider than shoulder-width apart.\r\n2.\tGently rotate your torso to one side and extend one arm upward while the other arm supports you on the floor.\r\n3.\tTransition fluidly into a forward bend by straightening your legs, then return to the squat before switching the rotation side. Keep the movement smooth, as if gliding through water.",
  "kniebeugeSchwingenName": "Swinging Squat",
  "kniebeugeSchwingenText": "How does this exercise prevent pain: \r\nThis exercise is a dynamic variation of the squat, where you gently swing your arms as you rise and lower. The swinging movements are an easy way to loosen your fascia and release adhesions.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStand upright, with your feet shoulder-width apart.\r\n2.\tBend your knees and lower into a squat while swinging your arms forward.\r\n3.\tAs you rise back up, gently swing your arms upward. Use the movement to create a flowing rhythm, as if softly gliding through the air.",
  "hufteLockernName": "Loosen Hips",
  "hufteLockernText": "How does this exercise prevent pain: \r\nThis gentle movement exercise aims to mobilize the hips in all directions. Flexible hip joints are crucial for relieving pressure on the knees and lower back. This exercise helps release tension and improve hip mobility, preventing pain in these areas.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStand upright, feet hip-width apart.\r\n2.\tStart by opening one knee outward and lifting your leg.\r\n3.\tSwitch to the other side and open the opposite side.",
  "standHuftCARsName": "Standing Hip CARs",
  "standHuftCARsText": "How does this exercise prevent pain: \r\nControlled Articular Rotations (CARs) are targeted, controlled rotational movements that improve hip joint mobility. Hip CARs help maintain mobility and thus prevent pain in the lower back and knees, which often result from restricted hip mobility.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStand upright and, if needed, support yourself with one hand against a wall.\r\n2.\tLift one leg bent, then open your knee to the side. Keep your hip facing forward. Slightly lift your heel upward and bring your knees back together.\r\n3.\tRepeat the circles in both directions. Focus on initiating the movement from the hip and consider placing your hands on your hips to stabilize your torso.",
  "schwingendesOffnenName": "Swinging Open",
  "schwingendesOffnenText": "How does this exercise prevent pain: \r\nThe swinging motion opens up your chest and loosens fascia in the upper body and arms. The dynamic movement gets your chest, shoulder, and back muscles moving and keeps your fascia flexible.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStand upright and swing both arms outward, opening your chest.\r\n2.\tThen bring the arms together and tap your shoulders gently from behind with your hands.\r\n3.\tMake sure the movement is controlled and fluid – aim to gently and naturally ‘open’ your chest.",
  "abschlussSchwingenName": "Closing Swings",
  "abschlussSchwingenText": "How does this exercise prevent pain: \r\nGentle swinging relaxes muscles and joints, improving circulation, which supports post-workout recovery. Feel relaxation spread throughout your body as you cool down.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStand upright and let your arms swing gently around your body, lightly tapping your hips.\r\n2.\tKeep the movements loose and relaxed, as if you're gently winding down. This gives your body the chance to release tension and find calm.",
  "standBwsOffnenName": "Standing Thoracic Spine Opening",
  "standBwsOffnenText": "How does this exercise prevent pain: \r\nThis exercise targets the thoracic spine (T-spine) by promoting spinal rotation while standing. It improves mobility in the upper back and helps open up the shoulders.\r\nA stiff T-spine can lead to overload in the lower back or neck. Regularly mobilizing the T-spine prevents pain in these areas and improves posture.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStand upright and hold your hands together in front of your chest.\r\n2.\tSlowly rotate your upper body to one side and open one arm backward, as if you were ‘opening’ your chest.\r\n3.\tReturn to the center and repeat the rotation to the other side. The movement should be controlled and follow your breathing rhythm – your back will thank you!",
  "standArmeAuswringenName": "Standing Arm Twists",
  "standArmeAuswringenText": "How does this exercise prevent pain: \r\nTense shoulders? Not anymore with this exercise! Twisting your shoulders and arms ‘wrings out’ tension and promotes flexibility, preventing neck and shoulder pain.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStand upright with your arms extended to the sides.\r\n2.\tTwist your arms so your palms face upward, then downward, as if performing a wringing motion. Alternate your gaze between the upward-facing palm each time.\r\n3.\tEnsure the movement is slow and controlled. Feel your shoulders and upper arms relax and become more flexible.",
  "standHalbeNackenkreiseName": "Standing Half Neck Circles",
  "standHalbeNackenkreiseText": "How does this exercise prevent pain: \r\nThis exercise gently mobilizes the neck by tracing half circles with your head. It helps relieve neck tension and improves cervical spine mobility. A flexible cervical spine reduces the risk of neck and tension headaches.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStand upright and lower your chin toward your chest. Tilt one ear up toward the ceiling, feeling the stretch in your neck.\r\n2.\tMove your head gently in a half-circle from one shoulder to the other.\r\n3.\tKeep your jaw and face relaxed, and perform the movement slowly to mobilize your neck without applying too much pressure.",
  "seitlicheSchwungeName": "Side Swings",
  "seitlicheSchwungeText": "How does this exercise prevent pain: \r\nThis dynamic movement brings your entire upper body into motion. By rotating the thoracic spine, you counteract stiffness and help prevent back pain.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStand upright with your legs about hip-width apart.\r\n2.\tSwing both arms side to side, letting your gaze follow your hands.\r\n3.\tLet your hips sway naturally as you move.",
  "schwungeZurDeckeName": "Swings to the Ceiling",
  "schwungeZurDeckeText": "How does this exercise prevent pain: \r\nThis exercise combines an upward motion with a dynamic arm swing. It improves shoulder and thoracic spine mobility. Opening up your sides helps prevent back pain.\r\n\r\nExecution:\r\n1.\tStand upright with your feet shoulder-width apart.\r\n2.\tSwing your arms upward to the ceiling and push your hip out to stretch your entire side body.\r\n3.\tSwing your arms from side to side. With each swing, your entire body stretches upward – imagine reaching for the stars!",
  "allOurExercises": "All our exercises",
